<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06247024 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06247024 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  FREMONT; DEVELOPMENT; MONEY; REGULATION  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A two-year process is expected to end tonight when the Fremont City Councilconsiders a package of new developer fees hoped to raise $118 million overthree decades to help finance new highway interchanges, parks, a policebuilding and a corporation yard.;   Developers have grumbled about the newfees during a recession, but the council has expressed support for theproposal as a way to assure that new development pays its &quot;fair share&quot; ofpublic improvements.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  FREMONT TO ACT ON DEVELOPER FEE PLAN  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The new fees, which fill gaps in the current system of assessments, willpay for only a relatively small percentage of the projects. To giveperspective to the proposal, the council on Aug. 20 adopted a five-year planto spend $361 million on building projects.;   That's not much solace todevelopers and companies suffering through the recession.;   'Not best ofeconomic times'; &quot;This is not the best of economic times,&quot; said MarkStechbart, director of local government affairs for the Building IndustryAssociation of Northern California.;   While Stechbart said associationmembers are willing to pay for new public projects, he wonders if the publicrealizes the fees will have a &quot;ripple effect&quot; on the entire community. The newfees will drive up home prices, he said.;   City staff members reply that thefees will have a positive effect on the community.;   &quot;It's going to mean thatthe city is going to be able to make traffic improvements to avoid congestionthat the city would otherwise face if it didn't get these fees,&quot; said FinanceDirector David Millican. The fees will also assure the city can build the newpolice building, corporation yards and parks.;   Want to maintain standards;&quot;We have to be sure we can provide the kinds of facilities to maintain thestandards of the community,&quot; Millican said.;   The council is scheduled to acton three fees: a traffic fee that would raise $93 million over the next threedecades, a capital facilities fee that would raise $13 million and a parkfacilities fee that would raise $12 million.; IFYOU'RE INTERESTED; The FremontCity Council will consider the new fees at a meeting that starts 7 p.m. in thecouncil chambers, third floor of the city government building, 39700 CivicCenter Drive.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  DENNIS AKIZUKI, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Alameda County/Am  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910903  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  371  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday, September 3, 199100247024,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>